The best approach for file system statics is the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package — it's battle-tested and already wraps the entire `System.IO` surface. No need to write custom wrappers.

Looking at your `ReportGenerator.cs`, I can see `Directory.Exists`, `Directory.CreateDirectory`, and `File.WriteAllText` in use. Here's how to make it testable:

### 1. Install the package

```bash
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions
```

### 2. Register in DI (`Program.cs`)

```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

### 3. Inject `IFileSystem` into your class

```csharp
using System.IO.Abstractions;

public class ReportGenerator(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string GenerateReport(string reportName)
    {
        var outputDir = Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable("REPORT_OUTPUT_DIR") ?? "/tmp/reports";

        if (!fileSystem.Directory.Exists(outputDir))
        {
            fileSystem.Directory.CreateDirectory(outputDir);
        }

        var reportPath = fileSystem.Path.Combine(outputDir, $"{reportName}_{timestamp}.txt");
        fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(reportPath, content);

        return reportPath;
    }
}
```

### 4. Test with `MockFileSystem`

```bash
dotnet add <TestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```

```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem();
mockFs.AddDirectory("/tmp/reports");

var generator = new ReportGenerator(mockFs);
generator.GenerateReport("sales");

Assert.True(mockFs.File.Exists(
    mockFs.Directory.GetFiles("/tmp/reports").Single()));
```

---

> **Bonus:** I also noticed `DateTime.UtcNow` and `Environment.*` calls in that same class. On .NET 10 you can inject the built-in `TimeProvider` for time, and a small custom `IEnvironmentProvider` for environment variables. Want me to generate wrappers for those too?
